// The `prelude.mcp` sub-module: MCP in both directions, as ordinary agent values. Outbound, `tools`
// plugs any MCP server's tools into a program; inbound, `serve` publishes a program's own agents AS
// an MCP server for the extent of a subscriber. Both route to the runtime's `mcp` reactor (an
// in-runtime MCP client / server, like `http.fetch`'s in-runtime fetch — no FFI sidecar, nothing
// for the user to install).
//
// Outbound, the whole integration is one line — pick how the server authenticates with the `auth` sum:
//
//   let tools = mcp.tools(url = "https://...", auth = mcp.headers(values = record.empty()))
//   let tools = mcp.tools(url = "https://...", auth = mcp.oauth(name = "github"))
//
// `headers` covers anonymous access (an empty record), bearer keys and any custom scheme uniformly:
// the given headers ride on every request. `oauth` names an OAuth credential established
// out-of-band by `katari mcp login --url <server> --name <name>` and stored server-side; the
// runtime injects (and refreshes) its tokens itself, so no token material appears in the program.
//
// A tool IS an agent: the runtime mints one agent value per server tool, carrying the
// server-declared name / description / input schema (and output schema when the server declares
// one) — `reflection.get_metadata` reads them (that is what an AI loop advertises), and a call is
// validated against that schema before anything runs (a bad argument throws
// `reflection.call_error` without the server ever being contacted).
//
// There is no connection to manage: each minted tool carries its server DESCRIPTOR (the url +
// auth it was listed with), and the runtime (re)connects lazily per descriptor — reusing a live
// connection across calls, reconnecting transparently after a failure or a runtime restart. A
// header value may be a secret (`string of private`); it stays private inside the tool value
// (sealed at rest, redacted at user-facing boundaries) and is revealed only to the server itself.
// An `oauth` credential's NAME is not a secret — the tokens it names never enter the program.
//
// Inbound, `serve` mirrors `webhook.inbound`: the runtime mints a fresh, unguessable capability URL
// and serves the given record's agents as MCP tools there for exactly as long as @subscriber@ runs.
// The URL IS the key — possession grants access, nothing else does (the endpoint lives outside the
// bearer-authenticated API surface, and the token is generated fresh per call); when the subscriber
// returns, or the run is cancelled, the URL deactivates. `toolbox` doubles as the parameter type
// because `tool` is the TOP type of self-contained callables — any agent whose effects are handled
// (or are at most `io` and this module's throws) coerces to it, so a user's own typed agents fit
// without ceremony.

@"The MCP server rejected a listing or a tool call, or the transport failed (the server-reported or
transport message). Catch it to control retry — a retried call reconnects."
data server_error(message: string)

@"An `oauth` credential is missing, or expired beyond what a token refresh can fix. Retrying does
not help: a human must (re-)establish the credential with `katari mcp login`. Distinct from
`server_error` so a program can catch the two differently."
data auth_error(message: string)

@"Header-based access: @values@ ride on every request to the server (each value may be a secret,
such as a bearer key). Anonymous access is `headers(values = record.empty())`."
data headers(values: record[string of private])

@"A named OAuth credential, established out-of-band by `katari mcp login --url <server> --name
<name>` and stored server-side. The runtime injects and refreshes its tokens itself; the name is
not a secret."
data oauth(name: string)

// How `tools` authenticates with the server: explicit headers, or a named OAuth credential.
type auth = headers | oauth

// One server tool, as an ordinary agent value. (Type synonyms take no docs.)
type tool = agent never -> unknown with io | prelude.throw[server_error | auth_error]

// A server's tools, keyed by tool name — call one by key, or hand `tools_of` to an AI loop wholesale.
type toolbox = record[tool]

@"The MCP server's tools, one runtime-minted agent per tool. Each carries the server-declared
signature (for `reflection.get_metadata` and call-site validation) and the server descriptor it was
listed with (@url@ + @auth@ — a header value may be a secret), so calling it needs no further
setup. A missing or dead `oauth` credential throws `auth_error` (re-run `katari mcp login`)."
external agent tools(url: string, auth: auth) -> toolbox with prelude.throw[server_error | auth_error] from "mcp"

@"Publish @tools@ as a live MCP server for the extent of @subscriber@. The runtime mints a fresh,
unguessable capability URL and serves the record's agents as MCP tools there — each record key is
the published tool name, each agent's declared signature the tool's advertised schema. The URL is
the key: possession grants access, nobody without it can call in. @subscriber@ receives the URL,
hands it to whoever should connect (an AI session, a teammate's MCP client), and stays alive while
calls should be served; when it returns the URL deactivates and its result becomes `serve`'s
result. Cancelling the run cancels @subscriber@ and deactivates the URL the same way. The
subscriber's effects flow to the caller's handlers unchanged; the served agents are self-contained
(`tool` — the top type of callables whose effects are handled), so any agent fits once its own
effects are handled."
external agent serve[R, effect E](
  tools: toolbox,
  subscriber: agent (url: string) -> R with E,
) -> R with E from "mcp"

@"A toolbox's tools as a flat array — the shape an AI tool loop takes."
agent tools_of(toolbox: toolbox) -> array[tool] {
  // Iterating the entries directly (rather than keys + a re-lookup) keeps every read total: an
  // entry's value is always present, so there is no impossible-null case to handle.
  for (let [_, tool] in record.entries(target = toolbox)) {
    next tool
  }
}
